<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06079010 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06079010 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  STOCK; CHART  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Stock prices dropped sharply today after IBM predicted lower quarterlyearnings and the government reported the core rate of inflation rose inFebruary.;    The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials tumbled 52.72 to2,877.23 by 2 p.m. EST.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  IBM REPORT SPARKS A MARKET SELL-OFF  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Chart attached at end of article  </MEMO><TEXT>     IBM told analysts the first quarter earnings would be about 90 cents pershare, about half the median estimate made by analysts. The announcementdragged down the entire market because the world's largest computer companyhad led the market's rally over the past two months, said Peter Vandenberg, avice-president at Lehman Brothers.;    IBM's announcement appeared to hurt thestock prices of other computer companies as well. Digital Equipment Corp.shares were down $4 to $72.63 at midday, while Unisys Corp. was off 25 cents ashare to $5.63.;    Technology stocks were a key factor in the rise in theoverall stock market in recent months.;    Also depressing stock prices was aLabor Department report on inflation. Consumer prices, excluding food andenergy, rose 0.7 percent in February, the government said.;    &quot;The confidenceand optimism that prevailed among investors a few weeks ago has now beenseriously undermined,&quot; said Michael Metz, a vice president at Oppenheimer andamp;Co.;    Economists said the Labor Department's Consumer Price Index reportverified fears that rising inflation could impede further economic growth. TheFederal Reserve would be less inclined to cut interest rates in periods ofinflation, economists say.;    Meanwhile the dollar rose today against theJapanese yen for the third consecutive session, while stock prices fell on theTokyo Stock Exchange following a three-day rally.;    The dollar closed at137.98 yen, up 0.33 yen from Monday's close of 137.65 yen. The dollar now hasgained 2.33 yen in three trading days, but its close was slightly below itssix-month high close of 138.07 on March 11.; THE MARKETS; ...; The Dow Jonesaverage fell 52.72 by 2 p.m. EST.; ...; April crude added 82 cents to $20.59 abarrel.; ...; In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.33 yen to a closing 137.98 yen.;...; In Zurich, gold was $362 an ounce today, unchanged.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  New York  </CITY><EDITION>  Home  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910319  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  CHART  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  355  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday March 19, 199100079010,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>